  "faq": [
    {
      "question": "When is fine-tuning cheaper than RAG?",
      "answer": "Fine-tuning tends to be cheaper than RAG at very high query volume once the upfront training cost is amortized, especially with small, efficient fine-tuned models. It also wins when the task requires style, format, or behavior changes that retrieval alone cannot enforce."
    },
    {
      "question": "When is RAG cheaper than fine-tuning?",
      "answer": "RAG is usually cheaper when knowledge changes frequently, when you have many documents to ground answers in, or when query volume is low enough that paying per query is cheaper than training and hosting a custom model."
    },
    {
      "question": "Can I combine fine-tuning and RAG?",
      "answer": "Yes. Many production agents use a fine-tuned model for tone, format, and task behavior, while RAG supplies up-to-date facts and source citations. This hybrid is often the highest-quality and most maintainable architecture."
    },
    {
      "question": "Does this calculator include data preparation cost?",
      "answer": "No. Data labeling, cleaning, and evaluation are excluded. Use the AI Agent Data Labeling Cost Calculator and Synthetic Data Generator Cost Calculator for those budgets."
    },
    {
      "question": "Which is better for accuracy?",
      "answer": "It depends on the failure mode. RAG reduces hallucinations on factual questions by grounding answers in source documents. Fine-tuning improves style, format adherence, and narrow-domain reasoning. For best accuracy, combine both."
    }
  ]
